a, forewing; b, hind wing; c, 3rd and 4th sternite, dorsal view, showing inner sclerotization; d, 3rd and 4th sternite, ventral view, showing abdominal apodemes; e, abdominal apodemes; f, genital capsule; g, pygofer dorsal appendage; h, subgenital plate, style, connective and the 9th sternite, dorsal view; i, subgenital plate, ventral view; j, style, lateral view; k, connective; l, aedeagus, lateral view; m, aedeagus, ventral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8302975E754D985DB7EEFF00FC1FFF33" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,751]" box="[199,938,151,175]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">
Male 
<number id="35758579754D985DB62EFF00FEA3FF33" box="[263,278,151,175]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" value="2.0">2</number>
S abdominal apodemes narrow, extended to fourth sternite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8302975E754D985DB7EEFF2BFA85FE53" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,751]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">
Male pygofer side well sclerotized, with numerous membranous pits, caudal margin truncate, inner side with two pairs of well pigmented separate lobes, dorsal pair darker, nephroid in dorsal view, fused to each other and basal opening of aedeagal shaft, ventral pair ornamented with small blunt denticuli dorsally, ventral part curled dorsolaterad and forming semi-cylinder; two pairs of appendages at lower part of pygofer present (upper pair here interpreted as pygofer dorsal appendage shifted well ventrad). Subgenital plate narrow, setosity poorly developed, with 
<number id="35758579754D985DB7FAFEF8FF48FE1B" box="[211,253,367,391]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
macrosetae near lateral margin and some short rigid microsetae on distal disc. Style greatly reduced, linear. Connective distinctive, extremely large and compressed, manubrium, lateral arms and central lobe not differentiated. Aedeagus tubular; dorsal apodeme and preatrium rudimentary, gonopore terminal, ventral.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CBA7C4D5754D985DB7EEFE4BFD62FD8B" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8302975E754D985DB7EEFE4BFD62FD8B" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,751]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">
<emphasis id="B1C94B4C754D985DB7EEFE4BFEFBFE68" bold="true" box="[199,334,476,500]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name is derived from the Latin word “ 
<emphasis id="B1C94B4C754D985DB4B3FE4BFBBBFE68" box="[922,1038,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">variolosus</emphasis>
” meaning “spotted” in view of the numerous pits on the body. The gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CBA7C4D5754D985DB7EEFDB4FBDAFD73" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8302975E754D985DB7EEFDB4FBDAFD73" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,751]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">
<emphasis id="B1C94B4C754D985DB7EEFDB4FEF4FDA0" bold="true" box="[199,321,547,572]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new genus is most closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="44BDECDD754D985DB439FDB3FBD1FDA0" authority="Dworakowska, 1984" authorityName="Dworakowska" authorityYear="1984" box="[784,1124,548,572]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Otbatara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1C94B4C754D985DB439FDB3FCC2FDA0" box="[784,887,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">Otbatara</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="E72CEAAF754D985DB455FDB3FBD1FDA0" author="Dworakowska" box="[892,1124,548,572]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" refString="Dworakowska, I. (1984) Studies on Typhlocybinae of Malaysia and Singapore (Homoptera, Auchenorrhyncha, Cicadellidae). Reichenbachia, 22 (1), 1 - 21." type="journal article" year="1984">
Dworakowska, 
<quantity id="44453ABB754D985DB305FDB3FBD1FDA0" box="[1068,1124,548,572]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.03936" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" unit="in" value="1984.0">1984</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in body shape, the presence of numerous conspicuous pits on the body, and shape and size of the style, but differs in having the pygofer side without macrosetae at the lower basal angle, with two separate lobes distally, the subgenital plates not fused and the connective compressed. 
<taxonomicName id="44BDECDD754D985DB682FD07FDA2FD34" box="[427,535,656,680]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Variolosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="B1C94B4C754D985DB682FD07FDA2FD34" box="[427,535,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">Variolosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="AAFAF637754D985DB534FD07FDDFFD3B" box="[541,618,656,680]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is also similar to 
<taxonomicName id="44BDECDD754D985DB41AFD07FB32FD3B" authority="Dworakowska, 1972" authorityName="Dworakowska" authorityYear="1972" box="[819,1159,655,680]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Eldama" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1C94B4C754D985DB41AFD07FC3FFD34" box="[819,906,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">Eldama</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="E72CEAAF754D985DB4BBFD18FB32FD3B" author="Dworakowska" box="[914,1159,655,679]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" refString="Dworakowska, I. (1972 a) On some Oriental Erythroneurini (Auchenorrhyncha, Cicadellidae, Typhlocybinae). Bulletin de l'Academie Polonaise des Sciences. Serie des Sciences Biologiques, 20 (6), 395 - 405." type="journal article" year="1972" yearSuffix="a">
Dworakowska, 
<number id="35758579754D985DB36BFD18FBCFFD3B" box="[1090,1146,655,679]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" value="1972.0">1972</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in body shape, presence of numerous conspicuous pits, shape of the style, and reduced setosity of the subgenital plate, but the pygofer has two additional lobes, pygofer appendages are present and the connective is compressed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
